reviews.text:
I've been to this venue a couple times over the last 15 years, both during its Electric Factory days and now as Franklin Music Hall. I've attended events as a VIP with early access, and I've utilized both General Admission and Accessibility Seating. I've never been in the upstairs, though.

The venue is well staffed, and everyone is always kind and accommodating. It always appears to be very clean and the bathrooms are well maintained. There is a large bar and a small refreshments area on the main level, which both run efficiently. Both areas have caffiene free, sugar free and alcohol free options.

The acoustics have always been satisfactory for every show I've been to, and there literally is never a bad view of the stage from anywhere in the building. No matter if you're at the rail or not, you always feel "up close".

If you require Accessible Seating and you use a wheelchair or other assistive device, it is important to point out that the Accessible Seating area is a relatively small raised wooden platform toward the back of the main floor, beside the bar. Visibility from the platform is fine for the most part, but patrons who have brought drinks over from the bar tend to want to hang around right at the railings on the platform having conversations and setting their drinks on the wide rail.
Of course it's important to note that there was a staff member standing on the ramp to the platform at all times so if there was any problem it could easily have been brought to their attention and rectified (and all the staff and security members were GREAT!). It just has the potential to be rather distracting from the show.

All in all, this is a great spot to catch a show!

reviews.text:
The Tarrytown Music Hall is a first class and top quality performance arts venue based in Tarrytown, New York.

Built and opened during the 19th Century, the Tarrytown Music Hall is considered Westchester County’s oldest theatre. The building was designed by architect, Philip Edmund and it features numerous Queen Anne style characteristics such as its pyramidal or hipped roof reflecting pyramidal massing. Throughout the 20th Century, it has hosted prominent musical icons ranging from Louis Armstrong & Miles Davis.

In December of 2023, I brought and treated my wife and myself to attend the “Nutcracker Performed By The New York Theater Ballet” at the Tarrytown Music Hall and we very much enjoyed the show. Our favorite parts of the show were the “Russian Dance” the “Waltz of the Snowflakes” & “The Nutcracker Mouse King Battle.”

Everyone performed brilliantly, and the theater’s acoustics certainly helped elevate the performance. The theater provides comfortable seats for its guests and great views of the stage and the performers

Both my wife and I would like to thank the Tarrytown Music Hall for providing us with a great experience and definitely recommend for everyone to attend and watch a show at this wonderful music venue!!!

This is a very beautiful, old theater, set in the heart of Tarrytown. The seats are comfortable and there is a lot of room between the rows so you don't have to get up when someone needs to enter/exit the row. There is a pay parking lot at the bottom of the hill near the train station - it's doubtful you'll find parking available on the street. We saw Leonid & Friends there, a Chicago cover band. They were absolutely fantastic. My only complaint was that their voices were a bit muddy. I get a kick out of the negative reviews regarding the parking garage and the time it takes to get out after a concert. It does not take an engineering degree  to figure out that there will be a wait when nearly 2,000 folks exit a building at the same time. Duh....get into line, turn your car off, put it in park, and then neutral and let it roll when the line moves a tad. Take out your phone and catch up on your social media. I do not think the police are patrolling the garage and giving out 'distracted driving' tickets.

First time experience of the theater and it is very well done! The beautiful light wood interior is carried throughout the theater. The acoustics created a personal experience wherever you sit.

What to wear? Business casual or go all out!  There's a lot of walking and stairs so ladies, give some thought to your shoes.  The floors are tiled and wood, very little carpet.  The music center was actually warm, during the second half we did feel some cool air. I would advise wearing layered clothing.

I have some tall family members and tend to find seating where anyone behind us can see.  This issue was already addressed by the seating itself. Seating was comfortable and offered plenty of leg room.

We utilized the Valet parking. As you enter from The Circle your eyes are drawn straight up to the mountain of stairs. There are elevators at this level. Any questions can be answered by the Greeting Staff located just inside the entrance.

Once you reach the top of the stairs is the Ticket Que for pickup or purchase if you haven't purchased online. I have a Strathmore account makes everything super easy. As you pass this area have your tickets or QR code ready to be scanned. Well organized!

As you walk along the main hallway you will be walking the perimeter going towards the on-site restaurant.  Plenty of tables to grab a bite to eat and meet up with family or friends. Checkout the menu and see if something catches your fancy. There is a way to pre-order but we didn't take advantage of the kitchen.  Someone in our group did get some sweet treats cookies and a tray bar slivers which were delicious.  Across from the Kitchen I noticed a bar set up which appeared to offer mix drinks and wine.

The building is quick to learn but there are no directory signs to orient you as to where you are and how far to your seat.

We did descend 2 flights to reach our seating level. At the end, we then climbed these 2 flights. I did notice an elevator not sure if it was available for general use or if you need assistance and a Staff Member needs to operate. There are restrooms on this level.

We attended Mannheim Steamroller and the posted picture was from Right Box #16.
Very good venue with nice acoustics. What’s not to like? We come to concerts here, my kid rehearses and performs here, I took music lessons here, we jog around or into here. Simply a wonderful place!
I saw the hip-hop nutcracker here and I absolutely loved it! The old bay kettle chips were wonderful as well!

The location was beautiful. It was an added bonus that parking is complimentary. The staff were all respectful, and accommodating. I feel as though there are no bad seats at all. The building was clean throughout. The sound was also amazing!

Sala São Paulo is an A-grade, first class concert venue.
Room acoustics is excellent. Sitting is sufficiently comfortable and stage view is uniformly good.
It is located in downtown São Paulo, but is easily accessible via subway, train (stations are right next doors and directly connected to Sala São Paulo) or car (on-site parking facility available).
OSESP, the orchestra, is simply excellent. And their rendition of Carmina Burana is noteworthy.

It is a concert hall where we can feel good echo of sound. There are sometimes complimentary concert. It’s worth to go and listen melodic atmospheres.
They have parking lot.
Surrounding area is danger so it’s better to park there.

It is a beautiful place to have both visual delight at seeing the Sala itself as well as auditory experience by listening to the musicians performing. It's food for the soul. One feels privileged  to be there. Before the symphonic, people sit have either soup or a glass of wine or browse the pretty gift shop.

I recommend visiting Sala Sao Paulo for an unforgettable music experience. The Rachmaninoff 2nd Symphony performed by the Sao Paulo Symphony Orchestra and conducted by Louis Langree was a remarkable highlight. The concert hall has exceptional acoustics and is truly breathtaking.

It's a really nice surprise!
We had a great experience tonight.
The café shop deserves a visit, the banana cake was delicious.
Unfortunately I didn't have time enough to explore the gift shop.
I will return soon!

reviews.text: This is to Columbus what Bogart's is to Cincinnati: small and easily accessible historic venue with tight security, relaxed atmosphere, very friendly crowd, and in a sketchy but well lit area. Nice older venue, love the intimate feel of older, smaller theaters. Show was fabulous, check out Barns Courtney! Staff was friendly and great.

This is a nice, medium sized music venue right off of OSU campus. Located next to Midway, parking is easily accessible at the East Union Parking garage just across the street.  Security and concert personnel were extremely kind and helped direct concert traffic efficiently. The venue layout is straightforward with a pit and side standing areas on the first floor and a balcony on the second floor. There are two bars at the venue with a broad array of beverages for your standard concert markup. Only major complaint is the bathrooms. They are pretty disgusting with the main locks broken so a latch lock has been configured to the top of the stall doors. Overall, minus that, it’s a well maintained venue with good acoustics and great lighting. Would definitely attend a concert here again!

The standing room area wasn’t bad. there is seating off to the sides by the bars & seating up top in the balcony but i believe that’s Vip or costs more money to access that. i will go back to this venue.

In Austin watching a comedy with Amy Poehler and Tina Fey. It was a good show, worth what I paid to see them, although the seats in the Bass Concert Hall are super steep. They should also add side screens so that those sitting on the second balcony can better appreciate every detail of the show. This comedy was very funny, I recommend it. reviews.text:
We arrived at The Birchmere around 5:45 and the parking was already filling up.  In hindsight, it would have been easier to leave if we would have backed into the spot but everyone was nice when leaving and we still got out quickly and easily.

Walking up to the building, the first thing you notice are the beautiful murals to let you know that you are DEFINITELY in the right place!  After getting our line ticket at the box office we sat in the bar area waiting for the door to open.  They called numbers and everyone got into the concert hall quickly.  The seating is very close together but manageable...could be troublesome for handicapped and disabled though.

The servers were quick and efficient at getting our orders and drinks refilled.  The food was really good and it was nice not having to figure out how to eat when coming right from work!  The venue is filled with closely packed tables but right up to the stage! You could literally reach out and touch them on stage if you wanted to!

Overall and very nice venue and I would definitely return!

My mom and I saw The Voices of Motown Christmas show at the Birchmere. This was our first time and we had a great time. I didn't realize the venue is as large as it is, but it has a cozy feel to it. While there were a few folks dressed to impress, there's no dress code so you don't feel like you have to dress up. Come as you are. I was even more impressed with the food and the service. We ordered wings and the Ginger glazed chicken thighs with mac and cheese and smothered cabbage. What in the world did the cook know about smothered cabbage...it was delicious!!! Done right! My Momma was impressed! Our food was out within 20 minutes or less. It's a well-oiled machine. Their system works! And not to mention the free parking. A rare treat in the DMV. Overall, it was a great experience and I look forward to our next visit.

Ok, so my friend invited me to go see Will Downing. I've heard of him, but from folks much older than me. I decide I will go. I worked down the street from this venue, but never knew it was here as it is literally in the cut like a bandaid. I'm not going to lie. At first, I was apprehensive about the surrounding neighborhood because it was just that, HOOD. But after parking and going in, I found it to be rather nice.
They sell food and drinks here in case you don't have a chance to stop to eat. The wings are FREAKING FANTASTIC! We ordered two orders, and drinks, which were also good. The food arrived quickly, was piping hot, and so very tasty.
Will gave one helluva performance. OMG, it was an entire vibe, and I'm so glad I was there for it.
What an amazing venue! Food was delicious, service was outstanding. No bad seats in the place! Highly recommend

Great sound & intimate performances in an old school music hall. Been a bunch of times and will go back again. The stage brings the artists very close to the crowd so you get a bird’s eye view of the artists at work. Performers often comment on the intimacy and sound quality at the Birchmere that make it a legendary venue for both the musicians & audiences alike. The seating can get a little tight at sold out shows but there are really no “bad” seats in the house (aside from the columns holding up the roof). You can go early and get a Deli-number for entry into the music hall for the best seats. Food is so/so but the service is good and they have local craft beers on the menu. The bar has overflow seating where you can watch performances live on video screens if the show is sold out. With about 15-20 shows a month, they feature something for all musical tastes. Go see what live music should be at the Birchmere soon!

Great place for those who want to experience a European environment. Central tables with seats for 2 or 4 or more. Corner and side tables, more cozy spaces for groups of 6 or 8. Pleasant, recessed lighting, offering an atmosphere of visual comfort. It has 3 environments. The first with direct access and ideal for those with mobility difficulties, a second level, closer to the bar, has counter service, while the third area is a few steps up towards the back of the restaurant. The menu has several options of hot drinks and drinks. There's something for every budget. And if you want, ask them to make your own drink, I'm sure Junior (bartender) will help you. Still about the menu, yes, there is fish and chips. If you have any doubts, ask chef Rafael and he will give you all the assistance you need to try the best dish of the day. Regarding the service, I can only thank and congratulate Mari and Glaucia, as they were very attentive and kind. Later the dishes were delayed, when we said that we were waiting for the next dish to those who were collecting the table they were emphatic: "there's nothing left for you..." they just forgot to tell the waiter that the dessert had been delayed....

Food and ambiance are excellent, but the price of the dishes does not match, they are much higher than what other pubs in the segment charge. We ordered a lamb rack that came with 3 slats, at 169 reais. It was very good, but the value for the quantity offered was surreal. Other than that, it was tasty. The oyster gratin is wonderful, a strong suggestion for anyone visiting! It's worth mentioning that I ordered but they forgot to write it down and when we asked a waiter if they were preparing it he confirmed that they were and in fact it was only when we asked for the 3rd time that they started preparing it. In this context, it becomes unfeasible to practice these values, which are expected to provide differentiated service. Despite this nonsense, the attendants are polite.

reviews.text: The restaurant is inside a hotel and they have an amazing breakfast buffet.
Very nice place, great food.
One of the best places to eat well in Blumenau. Food always very good. Excellent service, and a nice place to chat. I love going with friends.

If I could sum up the experience of eating brunch at Villa do Vale in one word, that word would be "Help". It's a lot, a lot of food. And Fernandinho is hungry. Very, very hungry.

To make it easier, I posted a photo of the menu, it's obvious how it works, but let's go: "buffet" is whatever you want to serve yourself and "a la carte" we order and the waiter brings it (individual portions).

I understand that some people might find the $120 per person price expensive, but that's a mistake; firstly because we end up paying that in any half-baked hyped café with "gourmet cake" and a fulero coffee in a 35ml cup and secondly, when we have a meal, it's no use just looking at the dry price, but what the establishment delivers. And what Villa do Vale delivers is a special experience, unparalleled in the city, both in non-food aspects, such as ambiance and service, and in the dishes served. And of course, anyone who wants to can still do the math of trying to figure out the price of food, if it helps you feel better.

Everything served is delicious and special, beautiful food, prepared with care. Even if you get a simple dish, with salami and cheese, it's already very tasty, but then right next to it is the oyster au gratin. Even though you know you can come and go as much as you want, it's hard not to feel embarrassed and leave with a big chunk of change. As a good friend of all foods, I tried to eat everything available, but I couldn't. Eating also requires strategy, and sometimes we need to sacrifice novelty to invest our stomach space in old favorites.

I recommend going there with time. In fact, time is very important in a meal. I like to spend three or four hours in a restaurant when I go out to eat, I don't understand the rush people are in to get home, away from the special occasion, away from the food. For this brunch, take your time, enjoy the beautiful and comfortable hotel, make your own plate once, twice, three times and then order the a la carte. Enjoy, savor. Talk to your wife, think about Flamengo's defense. And eat. Very. We leave heavy, but we leave very happy.

The highlights of the buffet are the brigadeiro brûlèe (delicious, I ate about 9), oyster gratin (tasty and very well prepared) and the Blumenau sausage quiche, but everything is good, everything is delicious. Try to taste everything. I even ate watermelon - very good, although I recommend not wasting food space on fruit.

And let's move on to the a la carte dishes: the poached egg is a great way to start, very tasty, with that special grease that the breading brings; the shrimp and Sicilian lemon risotto, very light and with a lot of citrus flavor from the lemon, is the best on the menu; the penne with truffled mushrooms is very tasty, earthy and certainly better than the vast majority of Italian restaurants in the city (which makes us want to go back to Botic for dinner). The level here is different, much higher, oto patamá. It's the 2019 Flamengo of restaurants. And then you order the nest pancake and nutella and smear it all over before eating. No one is as happy as a fat man is happy when he eats.

When the meal comes to an end, we feel that fat man's happiness, but the sadness of having to leave that jewel of a place, wanting to taste that wonderful food once again. But it doesn't fit. It's just math. I hope to return soon for another brunch and I'm already planning a dinner with my girlfriend, to try Botic's big guns. For everything it delivers in terms of service, atmosphere and quality, Villa do Vale's brunch is the cheapest meal in Blumenau.

I'm a big fan of restaurants, I'm from Blumenau and was born here. Well, I went to see O Botic because I found out about it through Instagram. When we arrived at the place, we didn't like the lights (we went for dinner), an environment with lots of lights and very bright. For starters we ordered a burrata with figs which was delicious, one of the best I've ever eaten in my life. We chose a good wine to toast which was also pleasant and my main dish was a carbonara which wasn't that good, we ordered a dessert called citricolate which was very bad and we almost didn't eat it because it was so sweet. Finally, we realized that the restaurant sells its image very well but the menu is not great (very well prepared but lacks flavor), the dinner was (VERY expensive) and was not one of the best gastronomic experiences I've ever had, I wouldn't go back (maybe because of the starter) . Do I recommend? No.
